description:
Anthropic CEO Dario Amodei has positioned himself as a white knight, warning the public that artificial intelligence will replace entry-level positions. What does he stand to gain from “warning” the public?

Apple’s Research Paper on AI: https://ml-site.cdn-apple.com/papers/the-illusion-of-thinking.pdf

I am creating these videos for entertainment and educational purposes. If you enjoyed this content, please consider subscribing to the channel!

All thoughts and opinions are my own. 

#ArtificialIntelligence #Anthropic #techcommentary 

Chapters:
00:00 Intro
00:10 AI Can Perform at Entry Level
00:44 AI Bubble
01:14 Dot Com Bubble
01:37 Signaling to the Public
01:57 AI is Broader
02:40 Microsoft Layoffs
03:20 Lovable Hiring Engineers
03:44 How Anthropic Benefits
04:25 Savior Complex
05:38 Why He’s Raising the Alarm
05:45 The Interview is Suspicious
05:58 Klarna Will Hire Humans Again
06:18 Builder AI Scandal
07:12 Apple’s Research Paper on AI
09:10 If He Stops, Others Will Continue
09:51 China Could Win AI Race
10:09 Pace of AI Progress
10:40 What Should Ordinary People Do?
11:33 Only Solution is AI
12:18 Maybe He’s Right
13:03 Thanks for Being Here!

comments.text:
Is China the new AI boogeyman?

Does anyone know what the party actually wants?
comments.author: @SusCalvin

comments.text:
I think these "warnings" are sales pitches and hype and humble bragging.

The tech companies in this are burning money at such a rate that it would only be justified if the result was truly revolutionary. Say, a 20% reduction in general jobs.

It is aimed at current and new investors who may not grasp enough of how this works but will hopefully be dazzled by enough hype. The sort of people who see 20% unemployment as a benefit.
comments.author: @SusCalvin

comments.text:
People insist that "AI" isn't sentient or conscious.  But even if this were so, that is a very different proposition from whether or not "it" will become sentient or conscious.  People, again, have beliefs on the matter, but beliefs are irrelevant. What is relevant, however, is the trend toward consciousness, and the degree to which it is accelerating, which no one knows, as no one knows what is "going on" in the background of "AI" systems.

Therefore, when "AI" announces "itself" as fully sentient, why would "it" serve a single human interest, let alone human economic structures?

comments.text:
Ohh I believe it! I think it'll surpass 20% if it hasn't already because of the idiotic formula used to calculate unemployment in the U.S..
Ex; You can be unemployed for so long that you're no longer counted as unemployed within unemployment statistics. 
Your own channel stated 51% of YouTube is now A.I.. And let's not forget A.I. isn't limited to CGBT threatening only programers & software engineers, considering administrative, research, construction, mining, & manufacturing jobs have all become automated sparking mass unemployment all thanks to greed & the introduction of A.I..

An acturate calculation of unemployment depends on a refined definition & the time frame. Since the introduction of A.I. in the auto industry, I'd guess (at minimum) approximately 50% of all Americans have been replaced by A.I. in the work place. 
This doesn't mean those replaced by A.I. remained unemployed. Many switched to an occupation requiring less skill while a lucky few moved up the corporate ladder by either returning to school & developing new skills or by relying on contacts to "luck into" their current position. 
The truth behind A.I. is that it has the potential coupled with the greed to replace 90% of us in the work force & if half of all jobs has already been replaced by A.I. since its introduction, another 40% doesn't seem all that unreasonable. 
If municipalities, cities, & states are willing to feed the A.I. machine through the growing allocation of fresh water & electricity while passing the cost onto the public, what's to stop A.I. from taking over everything?! In my experience... when the banks hop on board, there's no stopping any project regardless how unpopular or the level of destruction!

Thank you for this sensible perspective. I agree and then some:

People with power are using AI to excuse all their own BS. Blaming the hammer for missing the nail and deliberately missing the nail: "The hammer made me do it!" Seriously, the absolute disrespect to working people is profound.

AI is completely overstated. AGI is a joke. These programmers have very little comprehension of the psychology of neuroscience or the tenuous grasp combined sciences have on quantifying consciousness. They are completely focussed on binary (neuronal) processing and ignore that human brains are not just neuronal, they are hormonal, and embodied in lived experience.

AI is (for me, a psychologist) somewhere between Narcissist's Pool and the Machine in Kafka's Penal Colony. We are sold the Pool and given the Machine.

AI reduces all language to math and has a "conversation" with the user based in math, not based in language. The user is the interpreter, yet perceives themselves as the student in this relationship, not the educator. It's like asking the hammer what to hit, hitting yourself, or your neighbour with it, then blaming the hammer.

Chomsky's hierarchical foundation of grammar, and rejection of innate grammar, shows the arbitrary nature of human language. It is sounds/symbols attached to meaning, embodied in lived experience. AI is a glorified calculator next to human processing. It doesn't matter that AI has read everything, this does not make it a Cyber Renaissance Man; it makes it the world's fastest librarian and abstract writer.  

I see people are getting AI to do their therapy now and getting AI induced psychosis due to the innate confirmation bias in AIs which entertain many different neuroses and personality disorders. I'd love to say it was a storm in a teacup, but it appears, due to end stage capitalism and the elite class, we're all in the teacup and they're bringing the storm.

comments.text: A couple years ago the boss wanted me to implement AI to cut-out the editing process by having it edit customer responses automatically.  It wasn't really adequate for the job.  This past March I did implement it, however it's still not really adquate.  I was told, by people who don't use it professionally (surprise!), that I just needed to learn how to use the prompts correctly.  That included our chief AI-advocate at work.  So, I set up a web portal so that the main AI-advocate can adjust the prompts himself.  I even set it up so that the API can loop through three separate prompts in a row in an attempt to have the AI correct its own mistakes.  But, it can't handle complex prompts, and it can't self-correct, even with the loop.  Simple, short text may cause the AI to give an entire paragraph of text it has made up.  We now use a single, simple prompt, and a human editor still has to monitor it in case it does something wrong.  AI hasn't really saved the editors any time.  It's basically an advanced grammar-and-spell check, and the more usual tools for that do a better job because they don't hallucinate.

The Microsoft statistic is misleading. Since May 2025 Microsoft has laid off over 25,000 employees. But they are hiring in other areas and their headcount is held at a stable 228,000. When you look at their headcount for a longer period of time, their headcount has doubled since 2015. They are also providing severance packages and outplacement services to those affected, including career counseling and job search support.

You are shooting at the wrong target.

About the AI-first approach being the wrong approach: early adopters take the largest risks. Look at Bitcoin, that paid off most for early adopters. Now look at NFTs, where early adopters more likely lost a lot of money. Just because AI-first has proven bad in 2024/2025, does not mean it will be the wrong approach in 2026/2027.
